R Notebook by Aditya Meruga

In this notebook, I will be covering data from the 131 players in the 2023 Volleyball National League.

Data Dictionary
Variable Name Variable Type Description
Player Categorical Nominal Name of player
Country Categorical Nominal Country they are playing for
Age Numerical Discrete Age of player in years
Attack Numerical Continuous Average attack per match of player
Block Numerical Continuous Average block per match of player
Dig Numerical Continuous Average dig per match of player
Receive Numerical Continuous Average receive per match of player
Set Numerical Continuous Average set per match of player
Serve Numerical Continuous Average serve turns per match of player
Position Categorical Nominal Position of player

Let’s start by cleaning up the data by redefining each variable!

VNL <- VNL2023

VNL$Dig <- as.numeric(VNL$Dig)
VNL$Receive <- as.numeric(VNL$Receive)

#specify which variables I want to visualize using boxplots
numerical_vars <- c("Attack", "Block", "Serve", "Set", "Dig", "Receive")

#transform the dataset into long format so it is easier to create the boxplots
VNL_long <- gather(VNL, key = "variable", value = "value", all_of(numerical_vars))

#create boxplots for each of the numerical variables with different y scales for each
ggplot(VNL_long, aes(x = variable, y = value)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Boxplots of Numerical Variables", x = "Variables", y = "Values")

Let’s create some bar graphs to compare the attack and defense stats of different positions.

# Reshape data to long format for plotting
VNL_long <- VNL %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Attack, Block, Dig, Receive, Set, Serve), 
               names_to = "Skill", 
               values_to = "Skill_Value")
# Create bar plot for each skill
create_skill_plot <- function(skill_name) {
  # Filter data for the specific skill
  skill_data <- VNL_long %>% filter(Skill == skill_name)
  
  # Determine the y-axis limits based on the data
  y_limits <- c(0, max(skill_data$Skill_Value) * 1.1)  
  # Adjust 1.1 factor for margin
  
  # Create plot
  p <- ggplot(data = skill_data, aes(x = Position, y = Skill_Value)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "skyblue") +
    labs(title = paste("Average", toupper(skill_name), "per game"),  # Title for the plot
         x = "Player Position",  # X-axis label
         y = ifelse(tolower(skill_name) == "serve", "Average Serve Turns per game", paste("Average", toupper(skill_name), "per game"))) +  # Y-axis label
    scale_y_continuous(limits = y_limits) +  # Set y-axis limits
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))  # Rotate x-axis labels for better visibility
  
  return(p)
}

# Create plots for each skill
p_attack <- create_skill_plot("Attack")
p_block <- create_skill_plot("Block")
p_dig <- create_skill_plot("Dig")
p_receive <- create_skill_plot("Receive")
p_set <- create_skill_plot("Set")
p_serve <- create_skill_plot("Serve")

# Display the plots
print(p_attack)

print(p_block)

print(p_dig)

print(p_receive)

print(p_set)

print(p_serve)

This data makes sense given that certain positions have to fulfill certain tasks. For example, liberos are strictly defensive players. This is why they have no attack, block, set, or serve stats. The attack stats also show interesting trends in how much each player is set to at a professional level. Now let’s compare the different stats to each other using scatter plots!

# Assuming your dataset "VNL" is already loaded correctly
# Replace this with your actual dataset loading step if it's not already loaded
# Example: If your dataset is in a CSV file named "your_dataset.csv"
# VNL <- read.csv("your_dataset.csv")

# Example dataset (replacing with actual data loading step)
VNL <- data.frame(
  Player = c("Player A", "Player B", "Player C", "Player D", "Player E"),
  Position = c("Libero", "Setter", "Middle", "Outside Hitter", "Opposite"),
  Attack = c(8, 7, 6, 9, 7),
  Block = c(6, 8, 7, 5, 9),
  Dig = c(7, 5, 8, 6, 7),
  Receive = c(9, 6, 7, 8, 6),
  Set = c(8, 7, 5, 9, 6),
  Serve = c(7, 9, 6, 8, 5)
)

# Select only the skill columns for correlation analysis
skills_data <- VNL %>%
  select(Attack, Block, Dig, Receive, Set, Serve)

# Create scatterplot matrix with correlation coefficients
p_matrix <- ggpairs(
  skills_data,
  lower = list(continuous = wrap("smooth", method = "lm")),  # Add regression lines in the lower panels
  diag = list(continuous = wrap("barDiag")),  # Histogram in diagonal panels
  upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size = 4))  # Show correlation coefficients in the upper panels
) + theme_bw()

# Print the scatterplot matrix
print(p_matrix)

# Save the scatterplot matrix as a file (e.g., PDF)
ggsave("scatterplot_matrix.pdf", p_matrix, device = "pdf")
Saving 5.59 x 3.45 in image

It seems that the three relationships with the most significant correlations are Set-Attack, Receive-Block, and Serve-Dig We can further explore these relationships using regression lines!

# Scatter plots

#Set-Attack
ggplot(VNL, aes(x = Set, y = Attack)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Average Set per Match vs Average Attack per Match")


#Receive-Block
ggplot(VNL, aes(x = Receive, y = Block)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Average Receive per Match vs Average Block per Match")


#Serve-Dig
ggplot(VNL, aes(x = Serve, y = Dig)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Average Serve Turn per Match vs Average Dig per Match")

These visualizations make sense because sets are what allow teams to attack, meaning there should be a positive correlation between both variables. It also makes sense that receives and blocks have a negative correlation because players with a higher amount of blocks are usually front row while players who receive are usually in the back row. This means that players with higher block stats will have lower receive stats and vice versa. I couldn’t really think up an explanation to why digs and serves had a negative correlation.
